Return to the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have introduced a bill to establish the organization of trade unions as a civil right.
"Just as unions die, so do middle-class jobs," said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
Therefore, I am proud to present the Employee Empowerment Act together with the civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities for discrimination on the basis of the organisation of trade unions as for other forms of discrimination – and thus stops anti-union forces.
Complementing the National Labour Law Act to create an opportunity for discriminated workers to organize a trade union representation to sue for justice in a civil court - and to obtain damages or penalties - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the other sponsors are proposing for their bill is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks trade unions have faced in recent years—in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country—Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand, and uphold labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to pass a constitution to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojos was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that the workers and their unions took a role in creating a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly acknowledged that "the rights of the workers to unification and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing the fact that the workers would have to organize themselves and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that stated explicitly: "The right to form associations to secure and improve the working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that restrict or aim to restrict this right are null and void; measures aimed at it are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights as adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the other authors added a guarantee that “everyone has the right to form or join unions to protect their interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to shape civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to form a trade union – and that this union would then be allowed to participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies – must be protected.
In fact, after these rights have been under attack in America, it is very wise to re-evaluate the American ideal, according to which the working people must have the right to unite and make themselves heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the workers’ movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions of people, work has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of employee representations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and fulfilled the promise of democracy.
Judge suspends law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to close
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday provisionally stopped implementing a law in Louisiana that lawyers say would have led to the closure of all five abortion clinics in the state.
This measure, brought to law by Bobby Jindal, Governor of Louisiana, in June and scheduled to enter into force on September 1, would force doctors performing abortions to acquire a patient admission right at a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
