"The plaintiffs can continue to work in accordance with the law as they strive to obtain these rights," Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling.
Within a month, a hearing is scheduled for the judge to bring about a more permanent decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of judgments against similar measures, saying that doctors would gain more time to gain hospital admission rights.
"Today's decision means that women in Louisiana are avoiding a devious law that wants to take away their health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and chairman of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who had sued on behalf of three of the state's five clinics to stop the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the judgment also extended to the doctors from the two clinics, who had not joined the lawsuit and also applied for admission rights.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws, with courts recently declaring such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key areas of a Texas law that would have forced most of the clinics remaining in the state to close were stopped by a federal judge on Friday.
Advocates for abortion and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, agree that admission rights require unnecessary restrictions from doctors.
Opponents of abortion disagree that the measures serve to protect women’s health, although some also welcomed the effects of closing clinics.
Only a doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has patient identification rights, the Center for Reproduction Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would no longer perform the operation for fear of its safety, the group said.
In their argument against the verdict, Louisiana state officials said they would not punish doctors for conducting abortions while their applications for patient ID rights were still pending.
