State and local tax filings for companies in the country rose slightly last year as economic recovery accelerated, according to a newly published study last week, and companies in the Washington area were no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland, and Virginia area collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local agencies in fiscal 2013, an increase of 3.8 percent over 2012 revenues of $26.6 billion.
The state and local tax burden of the companies rose by 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion, compared to 3.9 percent in the previous year, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after the several years of declining notices in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose more than local taxes, by 4.3 percent, according to the study conducted by the services agency Ernst & Young with the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the district’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from corporate taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland’s revenue comes from corporations.
Virginia generates the lowest tax revenue from companies at 28 percent.
Much of the increase in tax revenues is due to a recovery in real estate values of the companies, the researchers say, leading to a 3.7 percent increase in real estate taxes this year after the three consecutive years with growth rates of less than 1 percent.
While a large part of these profits came from major states such as California, New York and Texas, the procedure seems to apply to the Washington area as well.
Companies in the District, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid over $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, compared to $9.6 billion in 2012 — a 4.2 percent increase over the course of a year.
But the apparent recovery in real estate values in Maryland is not as effective in increasing state and local tax revenues, as here real estate taxes amount to just over one-fifth of corporate tax returns.
Companies in Virginia and D.C. pay nearly half of their state and local taxes in the form of real estate taxes.
“In Maryland, a large portion of real estate, especially in the tax area around D.C., is either owned by the government or by nonprofit organizations that don’t pay property taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, Managing Director of the Center on State Taxation.
Maryland is therefore forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, in order to provide the same services that other states offer.
The recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovery of the real estate market
Business revenues also seem to be recovering, according to the data.
Companies in the region reported income taxes at state organizations of $2.3 billion compared to $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland raised $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the highest amount in the region.
While the trend is going in the same direction, the local tax burden for companies is not rising evenly in all three locations.
The rise rate in the district was 4.3 percent of the national average, while the rise in Maryland was significantly higher, 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia reported an under-average tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
