Putin demands Kiev to start "state talks" with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday that the Ukrainian government cease fighting the separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on the "statehood" of the renegade region.
His spokesman, Dimitri Peskov, later made it clear that Putin did not mean that the territory of eastern Ukraine under the control of the separatists would become part of Russia, but that his status vis-à-vis Ukraine would need to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
Putin’s call to the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents, however, fits with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the beginning of the riots five months ago: helping the separatists to seize territories and pressuring the Ukrainian government to enable the newly proclaimed region of Novorossia to achieve factual independence for an alliance with Russia rather than with the West.
In an interview with state television channel Kanal Eins, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to recapture the areas held by separatists in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were captured in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently referred to the occupied territory as "Novorossia" or "New Russia", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary heyday of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who hope for soon-to-be peace talks during the campaigns of Ukrainian politicians for the elections on Oct. 26 and while government groups attack civilian communities in the areas held by separatists are "trapped in their illusions," Itar-Tass reported.
"We need to start detailed discussions immediately, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the status of the state of Southeastern Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin’s reference to statehood should be seen in the context of greater autonomy, which has been discussed by the Kiev leadership for months, in order to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the eastern territories the necessary autonomy, Peskov said.
It is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin spokesman’s clarity on correcting the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underlined Russia’s claim to leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the East as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million residents are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulties in annexing the regions of Donetsk and Luhansk in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million inhabitants are not Russians and pre-conflict polls showed a broad majority in favour of staying in Ukraine.
The autonomy addressed by Russian diplomats on international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine the power to negotiate their own trade agreements and external relations, giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area that connects the Russian territory with Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, which was annexed five months ago, is the home port for most of the Russian Navy, as well as an important trading port and historic coastal region.
In addition, the regions between the Rostov area in Russia and Crimea are rich in mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
In his inaugural speech on 7 June, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko suggested that Ukrainian legislation, following new elections, should consider additions to the Constitution to give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his notion of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to that of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whose arming and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin’s last call to Kiev to negotiate on an equal footing with the separatist leaders followed a further advance of the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks entered eastern Ukraine via the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoasovsk, which Ukrainian security officials fear is the first step of a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region to Crimea.
For this reason, massive civilian and military preparations have begun to fortify Mariupol, a steel industry port with 500,000 inhabitants, located between Novoasovsk and the narrow access to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of EU leaders in Brussels on Saturday and urged action to prevent another Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are nearing a point where there is no going back," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not decide on any concrete actions, the leadership called for the draft of further sanctions against Russia, which should enter into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaysk after two Russian tank columns and 1,000 soldiers entered the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, said Colonel Andriy Lysenko, a spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defence Council Reports on Saturday in Kiev.
The first allegedly 63 Ukrainian soldiers trapped by the Russian invasion of Ilovaysk were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured on Ukrainian territory a week ago, Lysenko said on Sunday.
